Session Set-up

When working in RStudio, it’s good practice to first clear the global environment and set a working directory.

rm(list=ls(all=T)) # good practice to first clear workspace 

# set working directory 
## modify to pathway of the folder where your data is saved 
setwd("C:/Users/mads/Desktop/Summer 2024/Doug's stats course materials/Markdowns/Phylogenetic Mixed Models")

Install or Load packages

Use install.packages() function if the package needs to be installed. If install.packages() fails, it may be easier to download packages according to instructions from their github.

It may also be helpful to open R session as an Administrator to prevent package installation issues.

Making a Least-Squares Consensus Tree from a set of trees

Here, I make a tree for analysis from a set of 100 tip-dated maximum credibility trees from a 10000 tree sample (http://vertlife.org/phylosubsets/)

If you already have a single tree for your analysis made elsewhere, you can skip to next chunk.

# load in 100 tip-dated maximum clade credibility trees (from a 10000 tree sample) 
my.trees<-read.nexus("C:/Users/mads/Desktop/Summer 2024/Doug's stats course materials/Markdowns/Phylogenetic Mixed Models/data_files/tip_dated_output.nex") # produces a multiPhylo object 

# make least-squares consensus tree (Lapointe & Cucumel, 1997) from a set of input trees 
tree<-ls.consensus(my.trees, check.labels=TRUE, rooted=TRUE,start=NULL, tol=1e-12, quiet=FALSE) # can set a "start" tree for the function to work from

# save the LS consensus tree to wd 
writeNexus(tree,file = "LS_cons_tree")

Import Phylogenetic Tree

# load tree in NEXUS format 
tree<-read.nexus("LS_cons_tree")

A caption 

# plot LS consensus tree 
plot(tree, type = "phylogram", use.edge.length = T, show.tip.label = TRUE,node.depth=2)

plotTree(root(tree,outgroup="Didelphis_virginiana"))

ggtree(tree) + geom_tiplab(as_ylab=TRUE, color='firebrick')
ggtree(tree, layout="circular") + geom_tiplab(aes(angle=angle))

Compute implied co-variance matrix as a parameter for models

spp_obs <- as.character(data$Species)
tree_trimmed <- keep.tip(tree,spp_obs) # trim tree to tips, indexed by species labels from the original data set
Dmat <- cophenetic(tree_trimmed) # distance matrix 
Rbm <- corBrownian(phy=tree_trimmed)
V <- vcv(Rbm) # computes expected variance and covariance of continuous trait 

# Warning message; this is a signal that the data further down the line needs to be in the same order as in the tree file

Data Prep for Models

To use ulam for models, data should be in a list instead of a data frame. In general, it is easier to build models with reasonable and regularized priors without first interrogating the data (blind priors) by converting all continuous variables to z-scores.

Here, 3 data lists are built for examples of models with different desired outputs.

Data List Name Description Usage
dat_list_1 all variables, with data cropped to rows with complete cases of TM variable models directly measuring relationships between TM and other variables
dat_list_2 TM variable not included in list, no rows are cropped from data models that do not include TM
dat_list_3 all variables, no rows are cropped. Missing TM values are included as ‘na’ models that can impute missing TM values 
colnames(data)<-c("order","species","habitat","body_mass","brain_mass","heart_mass","lung_mass","kidney_mass","liver_mass","total_GI_mass","stomach_mass","intestine_mass","spleen_mass","visc_mass","BMR","body_temp","diet") # variables renamed to remove units and capitalized letters; just easier for script writing, but not required 

# calculate somatic mass variable
data$somatic_mass<-data$body_mass-data$visc_mass

# calculate proportion visc. mass variable
data$prop_visc_mass<-data$visc_mass/data$body_mass

# log continuous data
data$log_body_mass<-log(data$body_mass)
data$log_BMR<-log(data$BMR)
data$log_visc_mass<-log(data$visc_mass)
data$log_som_mass<-log(data$somatic_mass)
data$log_prop_visc_mass<-log(data$prop_visc_mass)

# convert data from data frame to data lists for feeding to models 
# data for each continuous variable is standardized to z-scores 

# data list with complete cases for TM, used for directly measuring relationships with TM and plotting 
d.complete<-data[ complete.cases( data$body_temp) , ]
dat_list_1 <- list(
  N_spp = nrow(d.complete),
  BM = standardize(d.complete$log_body_mass),
  VM = standardize(d.complete$log_visc_mass),
  SM = standardize(d.complete$log_som_mass),
  H = coerce_index(d.complete$habitat),
  D = coerce_index(d.complete$diet),
  O = coerce_index(d.complete$order),
  BMR = standardize(d.complete$log_BMR),
  TM = standardize(d.complete$body_temp),
  Imat = diag(nrow(d.complete)))

# data list with no TM, use for models without TM 
dat_list_2 <- list(
  N_spp = nrow(data),
  BM = standardize(data$log_body_mass),
  VM = standardize(data$log_visc_mass),
  SM = standardize(data$log_som_mass),
  prop_VM = standardize(data$prop_visc_mass),
  prop_VM_raw = data$prop_visc_mass,
  species = data$spp_obs,
  H = coerce_index(data$habitat),
  D = coerce_index(data$diet),
  O = coerce_index(data$order),
  BMR = standardize(data$log_BMR),
  Imat = diag(nrow(data)))

# data list of all variables, na for missing TM values, use for imputing TM
dat_list_3 <- list(
  N_spp = nrow(data),
  BM = standardize(data$log_body_mass),
  VM = standardize(data$log_visc_mass),
  SM = standardize(data$log_som_mass),
  prop_VM = standardize(data$prop_visc_mass),
  TM = standardize(data$body_temp),
  species = data$spp_obs,
  H = coerce_index(data$habitat),
  D = coerce_index(data$diet),
  O = coerce_index(data$order),
  BMR = standardize(data$log_BMR),
  Imat = diag(nrow(data)) )

To make phylogenetic regressions, add scaled and reordered phylogenetic distance matrix to all the data lists

# dat_list_1
spp_obs2<-as.character(d.complete$species) # need to first re-trim tree to only have tips that have TM values 
tree_trimmed2 <- keep.tip(tree,spp_obs2)
Rbm2 <- corBrownian(phy=tree_trimmed2)
V2 <- vcv(Rbm2)
dat_list_1$V2 <- V2[spp_obs2,spp_obs2]
dat_list_1$R2 <- dat_list_1$V2/max(V2)
dat_list_1$R2 <- dat_list_1$V2/max(V2)
Dmat2 <- cophenetic(tree_trimmed2)
dat_list_1$Dmat2 <- Dmat[spp_obs2,spp_obs2]/max(Dmat2)

# dat_list_2
dat_list_2$V <- V[spp_obs,spp_obs]
# convert to correlation matrix
dat_list_2$R <- dat_list_2$V/max(V)
dat_list_2$Dmat <- Dmat[spp_obs,spp_obs]/max(Dmat)

# dat_list_3
# put species in right order (should already be in correct order, but this is good practice)
dat_list_3$V <- V[spp_obs,spp_obs]
# convert to correlation matrix
dat_list_3$R <- dat_list_3$V/max(V)
dat_list_3$Dmat <- Dmat[spp_obs,spp_obs]/max(Dmat)

Phylogenetic Mixed Model with one continuous predictor and one continuous outcome

Example of one of the simplest cases of using Bayes to model the relatioship between two continuous variables while including phylogenetic distance as an additional predictor parameter.

Model 7 in Model Notation Index

m.tm_bmr.p: phylo of BMR~TM

# Model 7 in Model Notation Index 
m.tm_bmr.p<-ulam(
  alist(
    BMR~multi_normal(mu,SIGMA),
    mu<-a+b_TM*TM,
    matrix[N_spp,N_spp]: SIGMA <- cov_GPL1(Dmat2, etasq , rhosq , 0.01 ),
    a ~ normal(0,0.5),
    b_TM ~ normal(0,0.5),
    etasq ~ half_normal(1,0.25),
    rhosq ~ half_normal(3,0.25)
  ), data = dat_list_1, chains=2
)

Phylogenetic Mixed Model with multiple predictors and continuous outcome

Vm, sm, and H as predictor, as a phylo regression Model 8.2 in Model Notation Index

BMR outcome, a indexed by habitat, VM and SM each as a predictor, with phylo [model 8.2]

# Vm, sm, and H as predictor, as a phylo regression
# Model 8.2 in Model Notation Index 
m9.change.h.p<-ulam(
  alist(
    BMR~multi_normal(mu,SIGMA),
    mu<-a[H]+b_VM*VM+b_SM*SM,
    matrix[N_spp,N_spp]: SIGMA <- cov_GPL1(Dmat, etasq , rhosq , 0.01 ),
    a[H] ~ dnorm(0,0.5),
    b_VM ~dnorm(0,0.5),
    b_SM ~dnorm(0,0.5),
    etasq ~ half_normal(1,0.25),
    rhosq ~ half_normal(3,0.25)
  ), data = dat_list_2, chains=2
)

Phylogenetic Mixed Model with multiple predictors and continuous outcome that imputes missing continuous values

Vm, sm, tm and H as predictor, as a multiregression, TM imputed Model 8.4 in the model notation index

bmr outcome, vm, sm, tm and H as predictor, as a multiregression, TM imputed, phylo version [model 8.4]

# Vm, sm, tm and H as predictor, as a multiregression, TM imputed 
# Model 8.4 in the model notation index 
m7.p<-ulam(
  alist(
    BMR~multi_normal(mu,SIGMA),
    mu<-a[H]+b_VM*VM+b_SM*SM+b_TM*TM,
    matrix[N_spp,N_spp]: SIGMA <- cov_GPL1(Dmat, etasq , rhosq , 0.01 ),
    TM~dnorm(nu,sigma_TM), # add to impute missing temp data
    a[H] ~ dnorm(0,0.5),
    nu ~ dnorm(0,0.5),
    b_VM ~dnorm(0,0.5),
    b_SM ~dnorm(0,0.5),
    b_TM~dnorm(0,0.5),
    sigma_TM~dexp(1),
    etasq ~ half_normal(1,0.25),
    rhosq ~ half_normal(3,0.25)
  ), data = dat_list_3, chains=2
)

Save the models to an RData file in the working directory

This chunk saves the model as an RData object to the working directory so that it can be imported without having to run the model every session.

# save 
save(m7.p,m9.change.h.p,m.tm_bmr.p,file = "BMR_models.RData")

Load the models into environment

load(file = "BMR_models.RData")

Plot the model’s estimate of the phylogenetic effect in the predictive model

The effect of phylogenetic distance on BMR, represented as the prior predictions of the OU process kernel and as samples from the posterior of the preferred predictive model.

# plot effect of phylo in predictive model 
post <- extract.samples(m9.change.h.p)
plot( NULL , xlim=c(0,max(dat_list_3$Dmat)) , ylim=c(0,1.5) ,
xlab="phylogenetic distance" , ylab="covariance" )
# posterior
for ( i in 1:77 )
curve( post$etasq[i]*exp(-post$rhosq[i]*x) , add=TRUE , col=rangi2 )
# prior mean and 89% interval
eta <- abs(rnorm(1e3,1,0.25))
rho <- abs(rnorm(1e3,3,0.25))
d_seq <- seq(from=0,to=1,length.out=50)
K <- sapply( d_seq , function(x) eta*exp(-rho*x) )
lines( d_seq , colMeans(K) , lwd=2,lty=2 )
shade( apply(K,2,PI) , d_seq )
text( 0.5 , 0.5 , "prior" )
text( 0.2 , 0.1 , "posterior" )
